turns: Hillary Clinton's security detail arrived at a fruit processing company in Iowa with a second Scooby van, a mechanically identical GMC van with a nearly identical Secret Service escort vehicle. The second van is used as a decoy to confuse potential attackers. Clinton enjoys constant protection at taxpayers' expense because she is part of a former first family, not as a result of her service in the U.S. Senate or the State Department. The two Scooby vans arrived at Clinton's appointed location separately but left together in a seven-car motorcade. The second Scooby van's driver brought up the rear, allowing another car to pull in front of him. When that car stopped at a red light, the GMC van's blue and red flashing lights came on, and the driver zoomed into the intersection against the light. The Secret Service frequently deploys duplicates of aircraft and cars it uses to transport VIPs, including Marine One, the president's customized helicopter, which usually travels with two decoys.

A Georgia mother of six is homeless after a fire destroyed her rented condo in Decatur, Georgia. The mother, who was enrolled in school to complete her degree in business management, has been unable to find a new place to live while unemployed. She and her children are currently staying with a friend, far from their children's Decatur schools, where they are required to take a standardized test on Tuesday. The American Red Cross has assisted the family in their search for housing, but shelters have turned them away. The mother has started a GoFundMe page to raise money for a new place to live.

An Australian couple abandoned a boy born through surrogacy in India, and were repeatedly told that the child would be left stateless. Documents obtained by the ABC show that Australian government officials were aware of the situation, and that the couple was from New South Wales, where it is illegal to enter into international surrogacy arrangements. The couple told consular staff that they would be leaving the twin brother behind because they could not afford him, and that they wanted a baby girl to "complete their family." The boy would have been left stateless if the couple had followed through on their plans to abandon him, because India does not recognize surrogate children as citizens. The case is similar to the recent baby Gammy case in Thailand, where an Australian couple abandoned their son with a severe disability and only brought back his twin sister.

Kecil, a baby orangutan who had a tough start to life, found love and a surrogate mother in Maggie, an experienced orangutan mother, at the Brookfield Zoo in Chicago. After being rejected by his natural mother and two surrogate mothers, Kecil was given to Maggie, who has already raised four children and a fifth surrogate. The two have formed an inseparable bond and will go on display for the first time this weekend.

Paris Saint-Germain midfielder Javier Pastore has dismissed Eric Cantona's claim that he is the greatest footballer on the planet, saying he does not share the former Manchester United forward's view. Cantona had praised Pastore as the best player in the world, but Pastore believes Lionel Messi and Cristiano Ronaldo are a class above him. Pastore scored a brace in PSG's 3-1 win at Nice on Saturday as the Parisians reclaimed top spot in Ligue 1. PSG face Barcelona in the second leg of their last-eight Champions League tie on Tuesday, and must overhaul a 3-1 deficit to progress to the semi-finals.

Amanda Burleigh, a midwife, fought a decade-long battle to change medical guidelines on cord clamping. She believed that clamping the cord within seconds of delivery was unnatural and potentially harmful. She gathered evidence with other medics and succeeded in getting the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to change its guidelines. NICE now states that doctors and midwives should not routinely clamp the cord earlier than one minute from the birth of the baby. The cord should be clamped within five minutes, but left longer if the mother requests. The change means mothers get the chance to hold their babies for a moment while still connected to them. Despite resistance from colleagues and some doctors, Ms Burleigh felt a "moral duty" to challenge a practice that was not grounded in evidence.

French President Francois Hollande has vowed to show no mercy if French peacekeepers are found guilty of sexually assaulting starving children in the Central African Republic. Fourteen soldiers have been accused of abusing children as young as nine in exchange for food, according to a French judicial source. The French defence ministry has denied covering up the scandal, and an investigation was launched last year. The UN employee who leaked the report has been suspended, and an unnamed staff member has been suspended for leaking the report. The violence in the Central African Republic has largely pitted the Christian majority against mainly Muslim Seleka rebels who led the March 2013 coup against former leader Francois Bozize.

A shocking video has surfaced of a Texas pastor's wife attempting to resurrect a two-year-old boy who had died. The woman, identified as Aracely Meza, was arrested and charged with injury to a child by omission. The boy's mother reportedly knew Meza, but it is unclear if she is the child's mother. The incident took place at a home that also served as a church, and Meza used oils and prayed while trying to bring the boy back to life. The boy's death was reportedly due to either starvation or a fall from a chair, and emergency services were not called until four days later. The investigation is ongoing and involves both state and federal authorities.

John Higgins and Graeme Dott, two top Scottish snooker players, won their first-round matches at the Betfred World Championship on Sunday. Higgins, a four-time champion, defeated Robert Milkins 10-5, while Dott, the 2006 champion, beat Ricky Walden 10-8. Higgins is aiming to win the title for the fifth time, while Dott is unseeded this year but a proven Crucible class act.

Barcelona footballers Neymar, Dani Alves, and Adriano were all smiles after their win over Celta Vigo in La Liga, but their choice of matching denim outfits was questionable. The trio played a crucial role in helping their team return to the top of the league, with Jeremy Mathieu scoring the winning goal. Despite their victory, the players admitted that their performance was poor, with Mathieu blaming the international break for disrupting the team's dynamics. However, the French defender praised his defensive partner Gerard Pique for his impressive display against tough opposition.

Jose Mourinho, the manager of Chelsea football club, is reportedly planning to sign Koke, a midfielder currently playing for Atletico Madrid, in the summer. Mourinho is said to be willing to offer Filipe Luis, a defender currently playing for Chelsea, as part of the deal. Koke is a highly-rated young player who has been instrumental in Atletico's success in recent seasons, and his release clause is reportedly around £50 million. Chelsea's midfield has looked tired at times this season, and Mourinho is looking to add some fresh talent to the team.

Tom Ballard, a skilled climber, plans to climb K2, the second highest mountain in the world, 20 years after his mother, Alison Hargreaves, died attempting the same feat. Alison Hargreaves, a renowned climber, was swept to her death in 1995 while descending K2 in 260mph winds. Tom was only six years old at the time. Despite the risks, Tom plans to follow in his mother's footsteps and climb K2. He believes it is his destiny to do so.

UK Oil & Gas Investments claims to have discovered 100 billion barrels of oil in the Weald Basin, an area across Surrey, Sussex, Hampshire, and Kent. The company believes this could meet up to a third of Britain's oil demand within 15 years. However, industry experts remain skeptical, and one described the claims as "overly optimistic." The site at Horse Hill is believed to have the potential for "significant daily oil production." The oil is thought to be accessible, but fracking may be required to retrieve it. The discovery could create "many thousands" of jobs. The UK government owns the land under the homes in the area, meaning homeowners would not receive any profits from the oil found beneath them. The government would receive taxes on the oil extracted and may receive compensation from the oil company if they base their drilling site on the land.

The British Veterinary Association (BVA) has withdrawn its support for the shooting of free-running badgers in controversial pilot culls in Somerset and Gloucestershire. The BVA concluded that the first two years of culling had not demonstrated conclusively that ‘controlled shooting’ of free-running badgers could be effective and humane. The BVA still supports badger culling to tackle tuberculosis in cattle. The Environment Secretary promised to roll out more culls across the country if the Tories win the election. Animal welfare campaigners welcomed the news but said the BVA’s ongoing support for cage-trapping and shooting was ‘regrettable’. The Government's strategy includes cattle movement controls, vaccination in 'edge' areas around disease hotspots, and culling where the disease is rife. The chief vet admitted the benefits of the cull might not be realised in Gloucestershire due to extensive unlawful protest and intimidation by anti-cull campaigners.

The article discusses how modern technology can create problems in budding relationships. It mentions how social media and smartphones can cause issues such as checking phone constantly, taking photos of food, and comparing notes with friends during a date. The article suggests ways to avoid these pitfalls, such as keeping phones off the dining table, not changing relationship status on social media, and not bragging about Tinder matches. It also advises against using technology such as Google Glass to record a date.

Tottenham Hotspur will be without Kyle Walker and Hugo Lloris for their home clash against Aston Villa on Saturday, while Jan Vertonghen is a doubt due to a virus. Provisional squad: Vorm, Friedel, Yedlin, Chiriches, Kaboul, Dier, Vertonghen, Rose, Davies, Bentaleb, Paulinho, Mason, Stambouli, Dembele, Eriksen, Townsend, Lamela, Chadli, Kane, Adebayor, Soldado. Aston Villa boss Tim Sherwood will be without Alan Hutton, Ashley Westwood, Scott Sinclair, Carles Gil, and Aly Cissokho, but Aly could return after training this week. Provisional squad: Guzan, Given, Lowton, Bacuna, Vlaar, Clark, Baker, Senderos, Okore, Cissokho, Richardson, Delph, Sanchez, Cleverley, Grealish, Cole, N'Zogbia, Benteke, Agbonlahor, Weimann. Kick-off is at 3pm and Tottenham are the favorites to win at 4/7, while the draw is at 14/5 and Aston Villa are at 5/1. Referee is Lee Probert. Tottenham have won their last five PL meetings with Aston Villa, netting two or more goals in each game. Aston Villa have scored just six goals in their last 12 Premier League matches against Tottenham and never more than once in a game. Tottenham have gained 10 points from losing positions at home this season, more than any other side. Aston Villa have gained no points from losing positions away from home in the Premier League this season – the only team not to do so. White Hart Lane is the highest scoring stadium in the Premier League this season (51 goals). Aston Villa haven't won at Tottenham since 2008 when Ashley Young scored the winner in a 2-1 victory. White Hart Lane has also seen the most first half goals this season (27). Christian Benteke has scored seven goals in his last five Premier League appearances. Under Tim Sherwood, Benteke has scored at a rate of one goal every 87 minutes in the Premier League.

A mother who made the heartbreaking decision to give birth to her sick baby at just 20 weeks had her wedding dress redesigned so her tiny daughter could be buried in it. Jaye Cox and her husband, Matthew, decided to deliver their daughter Annabelle prematurely on May 5 last year after scans showed she had developed a serious form of Spina Bifida. Annabelle was born weighing just 290 grams at Canberra Hospital and her distraught parents were able to cradle her in the short five minutes she survived. The family, including her two older sisters Charlotte and Sophie, were able to take photos with Annabelle in her gown before the funeral. Angel Gowns created a replica dress for the family to have in their house and Ms Cox says she looks at it every day to remember her daughter. Angel Gowns is a not-for-profit organisation dedicated to turning donated wedding gowns into outfits for babies who pass away too soon.

A black police constable in Wiltshire, England has won a race discrimination case against his police force after he was not promoted due to the color of his skin. The employment tribunal ruled that the 40-year-old was passed over for promotion in favor of white colleagues after his internal assessments were secretly downgraded to make him appear unworthy. The tribunal also heard evidence that derogatory comments were made about Mr. Lungu based on his color, violating his dignity. The force, which has only 16 ethnic minority officers out of a total of just over 1,000, denied the claims, but the tribunal ruled that the Zimbabwe-born officer was unlawfully discriminated against on grounds of race. Mr. Lungu said he was left 'upset' and 'angry' after being penalized because he was black. The tribunal concluded that Wiltshire Police had singled out Mr. Lungu as a 'marked man' on grounds of his race. The judgment read: 'The reduction in the scoring has the very significant effect in terms of making it appear reasonable that the one black applicant for promotion was scoring lower than the 19 white applicants and should therefore not be promoted.' Despite his treatment, Mr. Lungu is still serving as a PC with the force. The Chief Constable of Wiltshire Police, Patrick Geenty, said he was 'concerned' by the findings and the force would 'learn lessons' from the case.

A parent taught their newborn daughter how to suck a plastic water bottle, which was filmed and has since been viewed over 190,000 times on YouTube. The video shows the parent gnawing on the side of a drinks container and the infant copying the action. The pair then bond over their shared interest in the simple prop.

A set of unique photographs of Bristol, England, taken nearly 100 years before much of its historic center was destroyed by Nazi bombing, have surfaced. The images, captured between 1850 and 1855 by photographer Hugh Owen, show the waterfront, city center, St Mary Redcliffe church, and other landmarks. The photographs, made in the 1870s from the original paper negatives of the early 1850s, are due to go up for auction tomorrow. The albumen prints show how much and how little has changed in certain areas over the past 160 years. The Fourteen Stars Tavern building, which was pulled down in 1857, can be seen in some of the pictures. The area of High Street has changed dramatically, while the view through St John's Gate at the Church of St John the Baptist has not changed much. The photographs provide a fascinating glimpse into the past of Bristol.

A pro-Ukip businessman, Harvey Boulter, is behind an effort to defeat a "golden boy" Tory candidate, Tom Tugendhat, in the Tonbridge and West Malling, Kent, constituency. Boulter is also spending £30,000 to defeat Liam Fox, who he forced to resign as Defence Secretary, in Fox's Somerset seat. Boulter's vendetta against Fox stems from a libel case in which Fox sued Boulter for defamatory remarks made on Sky TV. Fox resigned from the Cabinet in 2011 after Boulter revealed details of how Fox's close friend, businessman Adam Werritty, accompanied him on overseas trips as Defence Secretary. A Tory Party spokesperson declined to comment.

Aston Villa manager Tim Sherwood has written a letter of encouragement to a six-year-old fan who applied for the job after Paul Lambert was sacked. Despite missing out on the job, Charlie Pye was congratulated for his knowledge of the game and was offered a signed claret and blue football, a WWE wrestling figure, and some sweets. Sherwood wrote that he would aim to make Charlie and other supporters happy and wished Charlie's team Norton Lindsey success in their season. Sherwood also congratulated Charlie on being appointed captain and mentioned that the club would like to keep his letter on file.

Atletico Madrid beat Cordoba 2-0, with Antoine Griezmann scoring both goals, to move above Valencia in the battle for third place in La Liga. Saul Niguez also scored for Atletico, who now have 62 points from 29 matches. Valencia have 60 points and can reclaim third spot with a win over Villarreal on Sunday. Atletico also stayed close to second-placed Real Madrid, who they trail by four points. Sevilla, the only unbeaten team at home in La Liga this season, beat Athletic Bilbao 2-0 to move to 58 points in fifth.

An 18-year-old mother of one died from multiple organ failure after taking M-Cat at a house party in Tamworth, Staffordshire. The teenager, named as Abby Swinfield, was rushed to hospital in the early hours of March 30 and died a week later. Police have arrested one girl for supplying drugs, but Abby's cousin claims her drink was spiked. The family is devastated and Abby's son, who is believed to be three years old, keeps asking for his mother. A post-mortem examination is expected to determine the cause of death.

A playground in Tokyo has been found to have dangerously high levels of radiation, with readings of up to 480 microsieverts per hour. The cause of the radiation is not yet known, but it is believed to be coming from something buried underneath the park. The city has set up a health advice office to answer queries from concerned parents, and the park has been cordoned off. The incident has raised fears for the health of children in the area, and comes amid heightened concern over radiation in Japan since the 2011 Fukushima disaster.

Amir Khan has accused Kell Brook of only calling him out for the "one big payday" and believes that Brook is not a big name in the UK. Khan also stated that Brook is not able to face the world's biggest names and is only trying to win fans over by mentioning his name. Khan denied that he will face Chris Algieri next month and claimed that there are "some more options" on the table. Khan also stated that Brook is desperate to fight him but he will not fight during Ramadan because of his Islamic faith. Khan believes that Brook is not a big name in the UK and is not able to face the world's biggest names.

A Dallas architect, Matt Mooney, has transformed 14 shipping containers into a stunningly modern 3,700-square-foot three-bedroom home. The home, dubbed 'PV14', also boasts a 1,400 sq ft roof deck that can fit up to 150 people, a 40ft long swimming pool on the ground floor and a 360 degree view of White Rock Lake and the sparkling lights of the city's downtown. The designers wanted people to know what they were standing in when they stepped into the home, so they left the ceilings exposed and kept the shipping container gates unpainted. The walls of the shipping containers were removed, and columns had to be placed around the house to restore structural integrity to the materials. Spray foam was also used between the building layers to provide insulation. The upstairs levels are outfitted with maple wood floors to complement the views of the nearby park and lake, which provide a wallpaper for the house thanks to floor-to-ceiling windows.

Jordon Ibe is set to sign a new five-year contract with Liverpool by the end of the week. The 19-year-old has agreed terms on a deal which will keep him at Anfield until 2020. Ibe spent the first half of this season on loan at Derby County but returned to Liverpool in January and has made a notable impact in his eight appearances. Liverpool are also close to finalising an extension for Martin Skrtel and are in talks with young defender Jon Flanagan whose contract expires in June. Liverpool have agreed a new three-year shirt sponsorship deal with Standard Chartered worth around £30million a year.

Rik Mayall, the comedian and actor known for his roles in The New Statesman and Blackadder, died in 2014 without a valid will, leaving his estate to be dealt with under intestacy rules. According to these rules, his wife of 29 years and their three adult children would be entitled to a share of his estate, which could result in a large inheritance tax bill. Mayall suffered serious head injuries and nearly died in a quad-bike accident in 1998, but he did not leave a will despite this experience. Lawyers have always advised that people should have a valid will to avoid tax pitfalls, but Mayall did not heed this advice. His personal estate would be divided according to Government intestacy rules, which take into account marital status, children or surviving relatives. Mayall's children would be automatically entitled to a share of his net estate of £1,192,701 after funeral and legal expenses, meaning they could inherit an amount liable for inheritance tax. The amount of any tax payable would depend on the value of Mayall's chattels or personal belongings, which would go to his wife under intestacy rules. Mayall's family could seek to avoid the tax by drawing up a deed of variation to split up his estate, reducing any sum left to the children so it was below the tax threshold.

A group of Indian nationals and others who had been working in Yemen's capital, Sanaa, scrambled onto an Air India plane on the airport tarmac, carrying only carry-on luggage as they were evacuated during a small window when Saudi planes were not bombing the city. The passengers were exhausted by the push to get out of Yemen, which has been experiencing chaotic fighting. Air India is especially active in evacuating citizens from Yemen because so many Indian nationals work in other nations. Over the last few days, India has evacuated some 2,500 people from Yemen, said Gen. Vijay Kumar Singh, the Indian deputy foreign minister who's overseeing the evacuation. The flights are going to Djibouti, a small African nation nearly 430 kilometers (267 miles) away. Some evacuees are fleeing on boats at port cities such as Aden. People are leaving behind much more than luggage, as the fighting and lack of electricity have made living in Yemen difficult. The Saudi air force gave Air India a four-hour window to go to and from Sanaa and a specific travel route for a safe landing. The landing strips and airport terminal were untouched by Saudi bombs, but buildings on the outskirts of the airport and planes along the airstrip had been blown to bits. The loading of passengers was swift, and they approached the planes carrying boarding passes. The evacuees will most likely disperse to their home nations after arriving in Djibouti.

An Italian priest has been sacked from a religious order in Taranto after an online lover contacted the church authorities with a dossier containing alleged evidence of sex with prostitutes, role play, and explicit gay web chats. The priest allegedly favored sexual role-play scenarios in which his lover played the disciple Judas Escariot, and had to atone for his betrayal of Jesus by becoming his slave. The man claimed that he was contacted by the priest around six months ago on Facebook and that the priest revealed that he was gay during online chats. The priest also attempted to seduce the man and convinced him to leave his girlfriend. The Italian priest was sacked amid claims that he took part in gay orgies with a Swiss Guard. The Swiss Guard serves as the de facto military of Vatican City. The diocese confirmed that the priest had been dismissed but claimed there were no other prelates involved.

A new study published in the Journal of the American Medical Association (JAMA) has found no link between the measles, mumps, and rubella (MMR) vaccine and autism, even among high-risk children. The study, which was based on data from about 95,000 young people, found no association between MMR vaccination and an increased risk of autism, whether or not a sibling in the family was diagnosed with autism. The study's lead author, Anjali Jain, a doctor in Falls Church, Virginia, said, "We also found no evidence that receipt of either one or two doses of MMR vaccination was associated with an increased risk of ASD among children who had older siblings with ASD." The study's findings are consistent with other studies conducted over the last 15 years, which have also ruled out a link between the MMR vaccine and autism. Despite the consistent findings of these studies, concerns over vaccine safety, particularly in the Internet age, have proven difficult to quell. The study also found that children with older siblings with autism are less likely to get vaccinated, with a vaccination rate of 86 percent by age five for those with unaffected siblings compared to 92 percent for those with older siblings with autism.

A 12-year-old Yazidi girl was kidnapped, beaten, and raped by ISIS fighters in Iraq. The report from Human Rights Watch found that ISIS fighters are kidnapping Yazidi women and children as young as eight, forcing them to marry and convert to Islam, and raping them repeatedly. The survivors' stories come as United Nations investigators found evidence that ISIS is committing genocide against the Yazidi minority in Iraq. The report suggests that ISIS may be guilty of "war crimes, crimes against humanity, and genocide." The survivors need medical and psychological support to cope with the trauma they suffered.

On Monday morning, a former student named Kenneth Stancil, 20, allegedly entered the Wayne Community College in Goldsboro, North Carolina, carrying a long-barreled gun and fired one shot, killing a long-time employee named Ron Lane. Stancil is described as white, approximately 5'11", with a goatee, and a tattoo over his left eye. The suspect is still at large and an active shooter situation exists. One person was fatally shot and the suspect is considered extremely dangerous. The college website advised all students to shelter as there was an active shooter on campus. SWAT teams were clearing the campus building by building and students were congregating in the college parking lot. The lockdown was lifted as of about 10.30am ET.

The new CEO of Rotherham council could be paid up to £40,000 more than the outgoing boss due to negative publicity from the grooming scandal. The council will now offer up to £200,000 to candidates, rather than the £160,000 enjoyed by the former chief boss. The rest of the cabinet resigned in February after a government report said the council was 'not fit for purpose' and 'in denial' about exploitation, mainly of white girls by men of Pakistani origin. The HR chief said due to recent negative publicity, it may be necessary to consider additional incentives. The leader of the Ukip group said he was uncomfortable with the idea.

Cesc Fabregas will wear a special protective face mask for Chelsea after breaking his nose during their win over Stoke City. The mask was made by the Ortholabsport in Milan and is branded with Fabregas' initial and squad number 'C4'. Fabregas traveled to Milan with Chelsea medical director Paco Biosca to have the mask fitted. John Terry was forced to wear a protective face mask after fracturing a cheekbone in 2007, and Fernando Torres also wore a mask during his time at Chelsea. Diego Costa is expected to miss at least two weeks of action with hamstring trouble.

Andros Townsend scored a wonder strike for England in a 1-1 friendly draw with Italy in Turin, silencing his critics and providing motivation from naysayers like Paul Merson. This season has been topsy-turvy for Townsend, but England manager Roy Hodgson has kept faith with him, and he repaid that belief with a great goal.

A husband accused of trying to murder his cheating wife wrote her an extraordinary letter from prison while on remand, asking her to send him a suit for his trial. Joseph O'Riordan, 73, stabbed his 47-year-old wife Amanda eight times after discovering she had been having an affair with a postman. She was left with life-threatening injuries. O'Riordan, who was a councillor at the time, rang an ambulance after the attack and admitted what he had done during the 999 call. Four months later, while on remand, O'Riordan wrote to his wife from jail asking her to gather some of his belongings for his trial. Mrs O'Riordan, during questioning by her husband's defense team in court yesterday, sobbed and said she did not want to hurt him. The case was adjourned for 90 minutes to give Mrs O'Riordan time to regain her composure.

The UK is to open its first three proton beam therapy centres, following the success of five-year-old Ashya King who received the treatment and made a full recovery. Proton Partners International Ltd will open the centres in Cardiff, London, and Northumberland by 2017, with the first in Cardiff operational by next year. The announcement comes after Ashya's parents, Brett and Naghmeh King, fled with their son to Spain and Prague to receive the treatment after disagreeing with conventional NHS treatment plans. The centres will offer proton beam therapy, a highly-targeted type of radiotherapy that can treat hard-to-reach cancers with a lower risk of damaging surrounding tissue and causing side effects. The UK government has also announced plans to create two NHS proton beam therapy units, which will open in 2018.

The London Ambulance Service is recruiting paramedics from Australia and other countries because there is a shortage of trained paramedics in the UK. The selection process is held at five-star hotels and is so quick that applicants can receive an email the next day informing them if they have a job. The ambulance service is also understaffed, with around 1,250 posts unfilled across England, which is a tenth of what is needed. The increasing demand on ambulances means they are taking longer to reach the seriously ill, leading to many paramedics choosing to take up posts as 'advanced practitioners' in A&E, GP surgeries, and call centres for the 111 helpline where the work is less stressful and they can earn more. The ambulance service is also considering flying out to Poland to recruit paramedics. The cost of training one paramedic in Britain is £50,000, while each trip to Australia costs the ambulance service £90,000 in flights and hotel bills, but they return having hired on average 200 paramedics.

Chelsea Football Club has turned to the latest fitness technology to help them win the Premier League title. The club has partnered with leading wellness solutions provider Technogym, who have kitted out their Cobham training ground with state-of-the-art equipment. Players such as Eden Hazard and Nemanja Matic have been pictured working out, and Kurt Zouma has broken into the first team this year. Chelsea fitness coach Carlos Lalin has hailed the partnership with Technogym, and the club has had two players nominated for the PFA Player of the Year awards. Hazard is the hot favourite to pick up the award for his consistently brilliant form.

Babies as young as 11 months old have already mastered the fundamentals of physics, such as understanding how objects can pass through solid walls, and are surprisingly sophisticated thinkers. When presented with magic tricks that defy their expectations, they attempt to uncover the secrets and are more interested in playing with the ball than a new toy they have never seen before. A study by psychologists at the University of Missouri has found that infants as young as 13 months old can comprehend complex social situations, such as what constitutes bullying, friendship, and what it means to be a bystander. The researchers suggest that babies use what they already know about the world to form predictions and learn from unexpected situations. The study also found that babies who can accurately depict the human form at the age of four are more likely to be brighter in their teenage years.

Manny Pacquiao is training for his fight against Floyd Mayweather by running on the streets of Los Angeles and working on his core strength and footwork. He was joined by several fitness fanatics and his dog Pacman as he ran around Griffith Park and shadow boxed in front of spectators. Pacquiao has also unveiled a multicolored mouth guard he will wear during the fight.

A cat named Biso who had been stuck in a wall at a Cairo train station for five years has finally been freed. The cat survived thanks to an elderly man named Uncle Abdo who fed him scraps of food every day. The cat's plight came to the attention of animal activists after a picture of his tail was posted on Facebook. Animal rights activists, including Mounira Shehata, Marwa Elgebaly, and Rania el-Kordy, went to the station to rescue the cat on March 12, but the terrified cat ran away. The rescue mission took more than five hours, and a worker named Amr had to go inside to bring the cat out. The cat is still missing, and Uncle Abdo is searching for him inside the station.

At least 35 workers were killed at a dairy factory in Yemen when Saudi Arabian warplanes continued to bomb Shiite rebel positions in both the north and the south of the country. Today's airstrikes targeted rebel-controlled army camps in the Red Sea port city of Hodeida and hit warehouses belonging to a factory that produces dairy products. The jets drew return fire from anti-aircraft guns as the Saudi-led campaign to defeat the Iran-backed Shiite rebels loyal to Yemen's deposed president Ali Abdullah Saleh entered its seventh day. The attack on the dairy factory comes as Saudi Arabia hinted that it was prepared to launch a ground invasion in Yemen in the hope of forcing the Houthi rebels to allow current president, Abed Rabbo Mansour Hadi to return to the country, after he fled the southern port city of Aden last week. The Houthi's anti-aircraft guns returned fire before the factory itself was set ablaze. According to the medical center in Hodeida, at least 35 workers were killed, many of them crushed by the rubble or burned to death.

A truck crash on an elevated highway in Boston caused delays for hundreds of morning commuters. The truck collided with a car and both drivers were taken to the hospital with non-life-threatening injuries. Replacement shuttle buses were run for southbound passengers, causing long queues. The truck driver was identified as a 57-year-old man from Woburn, and the car driver was a 42-year-old man from Attleboro. State troopers are still investigating the incident, and no charges have been filed.

Mark McCall, the director of rugby for Saracens, praised his young players after their European semi-final loss to Clermont, stating that he has no intention of overspending in the post-World Cup transfer market. McCall's team, which contained five English-qualified forwards in the starting pack, came close to reaching the final but ultimately lost 13-9. Despite Saracens' millionaire chairman Nigel Wray's belief that the cap should be scrapped, McCall stated that the club is prepared to wait for the right player and is excited about the potential of their young pack, which could be the mainstay of the club for the next four to five seasons.

The decomposing bodies of four alleged terrorists who carried out a massacre at a Kenyan university were paraded in front of a large crowd at a primary school today. The authorities drove the naked, bloated corpses of the four men around the town in a pickup truck from the mortuary to Garissa Primary School. The attack at Garissa University College on Thursday left 148 people dead, with the gunmen shooting and beheading those who could not recite the Koran. Four other survivors from the massacre were found yesterday. Kenya's interior minister said the four terrorist gunmen had strapped themselves with explosives and when officers shot at them, they exploded 'like bombs' and shrapnel injured officers. Five suspects have been detained, including three Kenyans of Somali origin and two Tanzanians. The interior ministry said the three suspects arrested at the border had coordinated the attack. The militants said the barbaric attack was in retaliation for killings carried out by Kenyan troops fighting the rebels in Somalia. Kenya's President

Arsenal must make a decision on signing Petr Cech from Chelsea this summer or risk losing out on the goalkeeper. Cech is likely to leave Chelsea at the end of the season after losing his No 1 spot to Thibaut Courtois. Arsenal is one of the clubs interested in signing Cech, but they will have to overcome several obstacles, including Cech's valuation and Chelsea's reluctance to sell to their London rivals. Cech is considering moving to the Emirates Stadium, despite spending over 10 years with Chelsea, and hopes his long period of service will allow him to make the final decision on his next destination.

Sheik Joaan Al Thani has signed up French jockey Gregory Benoist to ride his horses in France, leaving Frankie Dettori to focus on the British flat season. Benoist will ride the horses that race under Al Shaqab's banner in France, except for dual Arc winner Treve, which will be partnered by Thierry Jarnet. Dettori will still ride British horses that run in France. The decision was made due to the expansion of Al Shaqab's operation, which now has over 80 horses in France and almost 100 in Britain. Dettori finished third on Al Shaqab's Moheet in yesterday's Novae Bloodstock Craven Stakes at Newmarket.

Lois Lilienstein, co-star of the Canadian preschool show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show," has died at the age of 78. Her son, David Lilienstein, confirmed that she passed away peacefully from a rare form of cancer on Wednesday night in Toronto. Lilienstein was born in Chicago in 1936 and moved to Toronto in 1996 with her son and husband. She joined Sharon Hampson and Bram Morrison to launch their singing trio in 1978, and the TV show "Sharon, Lois & Bram's Elephant Show" ran on CBC in Canada from 1984 to 1989, before continuing in reruns on Nickelodeon stateside until 1995. Sally Catto, general manager of programming at CBC Television, paid tribute to Lilienstein for her contribution to Canadian kids TV.

The video shows a world freediving champion, Guillaume Néry, jumping into the second deepest underwater sink hole in the world, Dean's Blue Hole in the Bahamas. He holds his breath and swims to the bottom before swimming back to the surface. Free divers can hold their breath for more than 20 minutes through sophisticated mind-body control techniques. The video was filmed in 2010 by his girlfriend and fellow freediver Julie Gautier.

A suicide bomber on a motorbike attacked the Kabul Bank in Jalalabad, Afghanistan, early on Saturday, killing at least 33 people and injuring more than 100 others. The ISIS terrorist group claimed responsibility for the attack, which was made by an offshoot called ISIS Wilayat Khorasan. The Taliban distanced themselves from the attack. The United Nations condemned the violence and warned that the use of suicide attacks in populated areas may amount to a war crime. Fears about ISIS involvement in the region have been growing this year, with former Taliban commander Mullah Abdul Rauf, who had become a recruiter for ISIS in Afghanistan, being killed in a drone strike in February.

Model and environmental scientist Laura Wells has launched a new eco-friendly swimwear line, made entirely of 100% recycled material. The collection is inspired by the ocean and features coral reef scenes throughout. The line includes one and two-piece suits in sizes ranging from 10 to 24, catering to all shapes. The collaboration with US brand Swimsuits For All's trend range, SwimSexy, was inspired by a conversation Laura had with the brand while working on a photoshoot. The primary challenge was finding environmentally-friendly material while keeping prices affordable.

The TrackYourDose app is a personal radiation tracker that helps users understand their exposure to radiation from various sources, including air travel, medical examinations, and natural radiation from the environment. The app uses a mathematical model developed by scientists and meteorologists to calculate radiation levels based on a user's location, flight details, and solar activity. It accounts for gamma radiation and cosmic radiation on the ground, as well as neutron radiation in the atmosphere. The app allows users to input their flight details and track their radiation exposure during travel. The app is available for iOS devices for £1.49 ($1.99).

Blue Bell Ice Cream has suspended operations at an Oklahoma production facility that officials had previously connected to a foodborne illness linked to the deaths of three people. The company is taking this step out of an abundance of caution to ensure that it is doing everything possible to provide its consumers with safe products and to preserve the trust it has built with them and their families for more than a century. The recall, the first in the company's 108-year history, began when five patients at Via Christi St. Francis hospital in Wichita, Kansas, became ill with listeriosis while hospitalized at some point from December 2013 to January 2015. Officials determined at least four drank milkshakes that contained Blue Bell ice cream. Three of the patients later died. Listeriosis, also known as listeria, is a life-threatening infection caused by eating food contaminated with bacteria called Listeria monocytogenes. The CDC has identified six patients with listeriosis between 2010 and 2014 that was indistinguishable from that found in the 3-ounce cup ice cream product traced to the Oklahoma plant. The company will conduct a 'careful and complete examination' of its Oklahoma plant 'to determine the exact cause of the contamination.' The plant has been voluntarily shut down, and the company says it will notify the U.S. Food and Drug Administration of its decision. The recalled ice cream had been shipped to 23 states, and the CDC recommends that consumers do not eat any Blue Bell brand products made at the company's Oklahoma facility and that retailers and institutions do not sell or serve them.

Jon Hamm, the star of the TV show Mad Men, was involved in a hazing incident at the University of Texas at Austin in 1990, where he allegedly set fire to a pledge and beat him with a paddle. The incident occurred during a hazing ritual that went wrong, and the pledge was subjected to two hours of brutal physical attacks. Hamm and seven other frat brothers were issued warrants for their arrest, and three members of Sigma Nu were sentenced to 30 days in prison. Hamm was eventually charged with hazing and assault, but the charges were dismissed before he began his ascent to superstardom. The incident led to the shutdown of the Sigma Nu fraternity at UT-Austin. Hamm has since admitted that playing the complex role of Don Draper on Mad Men has taken its toll on his psyche.

The UK has summoned the Argentine ambassador to the UK to account for recent statements by the Argentine president regarding the Falkland Islands. The UK has no doubt about its sovereignty over the Falkland Islands and surrounding maritime areas, and the Falkland Islanders' right to decide their own future. The UK government has announced plans to beef up defences in the Falklands and modernize its defences in response to the threat of Russia. The Argentine government has accused three British and two US companies of exploring for oil off the Falklands without permission and has threatened legal action. The UK foreign secretary has stated that the threats against those who do business with the Falkland Islands are hollow and illegal.

A Delta Air Lines flight from Tampa, Florida to New York City was met by firefighters in full protective suits after an odor of smoke was reported by the crew moments after landing at LaGuardia Airport. The firefighters used a thermal imaging camera to locate a potential heat source on the plane. Passengers were kept on the plane for about 45 minutes while the situation was resolved. The plane was taken out of service for an inspection and any necessary maintenance.

David Luiz, the defender for Paris Saint-Germain, has injured his hamstring and will be out for at least four weeks. He posted a picture of himself with a new hairstyle, a man bun, on Instagram and his teammate Lucas Moura joked about giving him a nickname for his new look. However, Luiz's injury will be a setback for his team as they seek to defend their Ligue 1 title and compete in the Champions League.

US President Barack Obama stated in his weekly address on Saturday that diplomacy is the best option to deal with Iran's contested nuclear program. He emphasized the importance of the deal's rigorous inspections and verification measures, which he believes will prevent Iran from cheating. Obama also acknowledged that there will be a "robust debate" in the US regarding the deal, but he plans to keep Congress informed of the agreement's details. The framework agreement reached between Iran and six world powers outlines a deal that would curb Iran's nuclear program and potentially lift economic sanctions. However, Israel's Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu has strongly criticized the deal, stating that it would threaten the survival of the state of Israel.

A 12-year-old girl with leukemia has been kicked out of school for poor attendance and academic performance, despite the school making accommodations for her illness. The school claims that they made many accommodations for the girl, but her parents say that they were inadequate and that the school is failing their child. The girl's mother says that her daughter is not skipping school to have fun, but rather she is too sick to attend. The family has filed a complaint with the Office of Civil Rights and is waiting for a response.

The study found that second-hand cigarette smoke can affect plants and cause them to take up nicotine from contaminated soil and plumes of smoke. This can explain why some spices, herbal teas, and medicinal plants have high concentrations of nicotine, despite none being allowed in insecticides. The researchers found that peppermint plants can take up high concentrations of nicotine from contaminated soils, as well as from smoke. The study suggests that the widespread occurrence of nicotine in medicinal, spice, and food plants may be due to other nicotine sources apart from the illegal use of insecticides. The findings also shed light on the hitherto unexplained success behind farming practices such as crop rotation and the co-cultivation of certain vegetables.

The video shows two chameleons fighting for a female mate in a brief contest on a property near the Amber Mountain National Park in Madagascar. The more aggressive of the two chameleons wins the battle and the defeated chameleon struggles to escape. The video maker speaks French and provides play-by-play commentary.

Scotland youth international Jack Cosgrove has agreed to join Edinburgh rugby club on a two-year deal starting next season. The 20-year-old Worcester Warriors prop has been capped nine times for the Dark Blues Under 20s side. Cosgrove is looking to add something extra to the Edinburgh squad and improve his game under the guidance of coach Alan Solomons. He is aware of the tough competition in the team but is eager to learn from players like Alasdair Dickinson. Cosgrove also praised the club's recent success, including reaching the European Cup final and advancing to the Pro12 playoffs.

Aaron Hernandez, the former NFL player who was sentenced to life in prison for the murder of Odin Lloyd, has been given the prison number W106228. He is being held in maximum security at the Souza-Baranowski Correctional Center in Shirley, Massachusetts. Hernandez was known to smoke "angel dust," a hallucinogenic drug, and his behavior became increasingly violent and aggressive after he started using it. He was also a heavy drinker and would often spend large amounts of money on bar bills and partying. Hernandez is charged with two counts of murder in separate cases, and he has pleaded not guilty to both.

Manchester City manager Manuel Pellegrini has confirmed that the club will be investing in homegrown talent this summer, which could impact Celtic's hopes of retaining Jason Denayer on loan. Denayer has impressed while playing for Celtic this season, but Pellegrini's comments suggest that the young Academy players are not yet ready to step into the first-team squad. City may bring back young professionals from loan deals to fill the gap, including PSV's Karim Rekik and Lille's Marcos Lopes. Celtic are keen to retain Denayer, but face an uphill struggle to do so.

Manchester United midfielder Ander Herrera reveals in a Q&A video that he wears his full name on the back of his shirt for superstitious reasons following his spell at Athletic Bilbao. Herrera, who joined United for £29m last summer, cites his good form at Bilbao as the reason for keeping his forename and surname on the back of his shirt. Herrera has forced his way into Louis van Gaal's starting line-up with a series of impressive displays and scored twice in United's 3-1 win over Aston Villa on Saturday, his tally now stands at seven goals in all competitions this season. He hopes to show more emotion in the future as United target silverware.

Porto fans gave their team a hero's welcome upon their return to Portugal following a 6-1 defeat at the hands of Bayern Munich in the Champions League quarter-final. Despite the loss, the team had reached the quarter-finals for the first time since the 2008-09 season, and coach Julen Lopetegui praised the team's efforts in the tournament.

The BBC has been criticized for creating a computer game called "Syrian Journey" that simulates the dangerous journey that Syrian refugees must take to escape their war-torn country and reach Europe. The game has been described as "sickening" and "in bad taste" by some social media users, who argue that it turns the suffering of millions into a "children's game." The game has been criticized for its grim outcomes, which include refugees being separated from their families, beaten and thrown into the Mediterranean, and sold to militia groups. The BBC has defended the game, saying that it shows the choices faced by Syrian families every day and has achieved over a million online hits a week.

Two of the victims of the Boston Marathon bombing have called for the death penalty to be taken off the table as a punishment for Dzhokar Tsarnaev, the bomber who killed three people and injured hundreds more in 2013. Jessica Kensky and Patrick Downes, who lost limbs in the attack, said they opposed the death penalty as a means of punishment for their attacker, urging others to "overcome the impulse for vengeance." The couple's statement follows a similar appeal made by the family of an eight-year-old boy who was killed in the blast. The victims' position is highly emotional and practical, and they call for Tsarnaev to be sentenced to life in prison without parole. The Richards, the family of bombing victim Martin Richard, also wrote an op-ed in the Boston Globe, saying they oppose the death penalty for Tsarnaev. The family is asking the government prosecutors to drop the fight for execution and sign a plea deal to send the 21-year-old to jail for the rest of his life.

Hamdi Ulukaya, the founder and CEO of Chobani, has settled a lawsuit filed by his ex-wife, Dr. Ayse Giray, who claimed half of the $2 billion Greek yogurt empire. The settlement came just before a court ruling on whether Giray could be named a shareholder in Chobani's predecessor company. Ulukaya's camp settled to avoid losing assets worth $1 billion to Giray. Despite the settlement, Ulukaya still faces business problems, including a product recall that led to negative EBITDA of $87 million in the fourth quarter of 2013.

Diego Costa has suffered a hamstring injury and is expected to miss Chelsea's game against Arsenal. He is likely to be fit to return for the game against Arsenal, but his participation in the game will depend on how the title race develops. The club is considering giving Costa an extended break to help him overcome his hamstring problems.

The England C team, which has been in existence for 36 years, may be disbanded as part of a spending review at the Football Association. The team, which is managed by Paul Fairclough and selects players outside the Football League aged 23 and under, has only played three or four times a year and has not qualified for the semi-finals of the International Challenge Trophy in recent years. The team's long-term future is uncertain due to the need to find £30 million to fund a masterplan to improve grassroots football, which includes the creation of more 3G pitches in urban coaching hubs. Some of the team's fixtures have attracted attention due to the elaborate travel involved, and the team has not played any friendly fixtures since February. Former players of the team include George Boyd, Craig Mackail-Smith, and Steve Morison, who all went on to play at full international level, although not for England.

James Haskell, the captain of London Wasps rugby club, posted a photo of himself dressed as Iron Man on Instagram to celebrate the release of the new Avengers movie. The highly-anticipated movie premiered at Westfield London shopping center with a star-studded cast including Robert Downey Jr., Chris Hemsworth, and Scarlett Johansson. Haskell, who started his career at Wasps in 2002, returned to the club for the 2012 season after spells with Stade Francais, Ricoh Black Rams, and Highlanders in New Zealand. The flanker has since become a key player for England and has surpassed 100 appearances for Wasps.

A woman named Stacey Eden stood up to a middle-aged woman who was making offensive comments about Islam on a train in Sydney. The woman was ranting about Islam, bringing up beheadings and the marriage of children while berating a Muslim woman for wearing a black headscarf. Stacey recorded a snippet of the conversation and fired back at the woman in defense of the Muslim couple. The Muslim couple told Stacey they were "very grateful" for her stand. The incident occurred on Wednesday afternoon on an Airport Line train. The police and Sydney Trains have not yet received any reports of the incident. The Islamophobia Register Australia group praised Stacey's actions and said they were disappointed by the remarks of the woman in the video.

Ursula Ward, the mother of Odin Lloyd, is moving forward with a civil lawsuit against Aaron Hernandez, the former New England Patriots player who was convicted of first-degree murder for killing Lloyd on June 17, 2013. Ward filed the lawsuit in December 2013 but it was put on hold during Hernandez's criminal trial. Sheff, Ward's attorney, said that he plans to resume the lawsuit in the next few weeks to hunt down Hernandez's assets, including his home in North Attleborough, which is assessed at $1.2 million. Hernandez's lawyer, John Fitzpatrick, did not immediately return a message seeking comment. Hernandez's fiancee and two-year-old daughter live in the home. The Patriots organization was originally named in the suit but was dismissed after agreeing that any money released to Hernandez would be granted to the

Britain has discovered oil in the Falklands, which is likely to escalate tensions with Argentina over the ownership of the islands. Argentina has claimed that companies operating off the Falklands coast are acting "illegally" in Argentine territory and has threatened to prosecute them. The discovery comes just days after Defence Secretary Michael Fallon warned of a "very live threat" from Argentina. Argentina invaded the Falklands in 1982, leading to a conflict that cost 260 British and 650 Argentine lives. The South American state still claims territorial rights to the islands. Britain pledged last week to invest £180 million over the next ten years to defend the islands, with an upgrade of a surface-to-air missile system and the deployment of two Chinook helicopters. The latest discovery could yield 100 million barrels of oil and shares in the oil-exploration companies initially soared to double digits after the discovery was announced.

A three-legged cat named Freeman was mauled to death by two dogs in a brutal attack captured on CCTV in Tarring, West Sussex. The attack took place in the front garden of Terry Rickards while he was away. The woman who appears to call over the dogs before walking off is believed to be the owner of the dogs. The police are investigating the incident and the large dogs, which were possibly Dobermans, were collected by someone who turned up in a blue car. The cat's owner, Tracy Lynch, is devastated by the loss of her family pet and the lack of concern shown by the dog owners.

A Chinese woman named Zhu Diandian has become an internet sensation after she shared pictures of herself dressing, walking, and sleeping with her pet pig named Five Flowers. The pig has grown to 187lbs (13st) since she raised it since it was a piglet. Her husband is reportedly 'tolerant' of the relationship, but the same can't be said for her pet dog who often peers enviously at the pig through a baby gate. Ms Zhu often posts pictures of herself and Five Flowers snuggled up in bed together, and has over 40,000 followers on Weibo.
